WEBVTT

00:03.786 --> 00:05.396
Bob Evans? Al Ruddy.

00:05.440 --> 00:06.745
I wanted to talk to you.
You got a minute?

00:06.789 --> 00:08.182
What can I do for you,
Mr. Ruddy?

00:08.225 --> 00:09.487
It's what I can do for you.

00:09.531 --> 00:11.228
I want to produce
for Paramount.

00:11.272 --> 00:12.708
"The Godfather."

00:12.751 --> 00:15.711
It's 58 weeks at number one.
Makes us looks stupid.

00:15.754 --> 00:17.321
And that's bad for business.

00:17.365 --> 00:19.062
Buddy, you've read
"The Godfather", right?

00:19.106 --> 00:20.803
I need you to produce it.

00:20.846 --> 00:22.631
The Corleones are my family.

00:22.674 --> 00:24.459
I have to be the one
to write this.

00:24.502 --> 00:26.069
Puzo's never written a film.

00:26.113 --> 00:27.375
It's an unwritten law
in Hollywood

00:27.418 --> 00:28.811
that you never hire
the author.

00:28.854 --> 00:30.378
I can't do this.

00:30.421 --> 00:32.075
Evans warned you
about hiring the novelist.

00:32.119 --> 00:34.208
So how do we fix it?

00:34.251 --> 00:35.948
Francis Ford Coppola.

00:35.992 --> 00:37.863
He's brilliant,
but he'll want to direct.

00:37.907 --> 00:41.650
Jews got the JDL.
The Blacks got the NAACP.

00:41.693 --> 00:43.260
Well, who defends us,
the Italians?

00:43.304 --> 00:45.349
Nobody.Well, I'm starting.

00:45.393 --> 00:48.091
The Italian-American
Civil Rights League.

00:48.135 --> 00:49.832
You're the rat fink
who wrote that fucking book

00:49.875 --> 00:51.355
about the degenerate singer.

00:51.399 --> 00:53.836
Sinatra wants us
to shut the picture down.

00:53.879 --> 00:55.490
Get me Mickey Cohen
in Los Angeles.

00:57.144 --> 00:58.275
Time to send a message.

02:25.797 --> 02:29.149
One! One! One! One!

02:29.192 --> 02:31.281
One! One! One!
One!

02:31.325 --> 02:35.416
There's a conspiracy
in this country...

02:35.459 --> 02:37.374
against Italian-Americans!

02:38.984 --> 02:40.638
The President,

02:40.682 --> 02:42.031
the Vice-President,

02:42.074 --> 02:43.467
the Attorney General,

02:43.511 --> 02:44.729
all conspiring against

02:44.773 --> 02:46.601
the hard-working
Italian people.

02:46.644 --> 02:49.299
- Yeah!
- We must unite!

02:52.563 --> 02:54.478
And the media,

02:54.522 --> 02:56.828
they carry the water

02:56.872 --> 02:58.830
for the corrupt politicians
in the government

02:58.874 --> 03:00.571
that tries to hold us down!

03:00.615 --> 03:02.660
Give me the book.

03:03.748 --> 03:06.055
And books like this trash

03:06.098 --> 03:09.972
only fuel the fire of hatred
for our people.

03:10.015 --> 03:12.235
And now the papers say
they're making a movie of it.

03:13.715 --> 03:16.108
This, my friends,
is a book of lies,

03:16.152 --> 03:18.328
and Mario Puzo is a traitor!

03:21.026 --> 03:24.378
Well, my friends,
this stops today!

03:24.421 --> 03:28.208
Our organization,
your organization,

03:28.251 --> 03:31.515
the Italian-American Civil
Rights League will fight back.

03:31.559 --> 03:34.344
We will snuff out the hatred
and the prejudice!

03:40.872 --> 03:42.831
Columbo, Columbo!

03:52.319 --> 03:54.103
Hey, boys.
Can I help you?

03:54.146 --> 03:56.714
Is this your car?
You Al Ruddy?

03:56.758 --> 03:58.542
Yeah, that's me.

03:58.586 --> 04:00.283
FBI.

04:00.327 --> 04:02.720
I'm Agent Hale,
this is Special Agent Moran.

04:02.764 --> 04:04.069
FBI?

04:04.113 --> 04:05.375
And, uh, and you are?

04:06.507 --> 04:09.684
Bettye McCartt.
Mr. Ruddy's secretary.

04:09.727 --> 04:11.555
Oh, right.

04:11.599 --> 04:13.296
So you were in the car
last night as well?

04:13.340 --> 04:15.255
That's right, yeah.

04:15.298 --> 04:16.604
Look, what's this all about?

04:16.647 --> 04:18.867
I already gave
a statement to the LAPD.

04:18.910 --> 04:20.434
So what are you guys
doing here?

04:22.218 --> 04:24.002
Well, we have reasons
to believe

04:24.046 --> 04:26.440
that you may have been targeted
by Mickey Cohen.

04:26.483 --> 04:27.876
The gangster?

04:27.919 --> 04:29.225
Can you think of
any reason

04:29.269 --> 04:32.663
why Cohen might have wanted
to scare you?

04:32.707 --> 04:34.883
Now, think real hard, hmm?

04:34.926 --> 04:36.754
Maybe something to do
with your business?

04:36.798 --> 04:38.103
Your personal life? Huh?

04:38.147 --> 04:39.061
Scare us?

04:41.019 --> 04:42.586
He tried to kill us.

04:42.630 --> 04:43.848
No.

04:43.892 --> 04:46.068
That was a warning.

04:46.111 --> 04:48.026
When Mickey Cohen
fires a shot...

04:50.333 --> 04:52.074
He doesn't miss.

04:52.117 --> 04:54.468
Is there a reason why you
guys are here right now with us

04:54.511 --> 04:55.991
and not arresting him?Again...

04:57.122 --> 04:58.559
Just a suspicion.

05:00.256 --> 05:01.779
How fucking comforting.

05:10.745 --> 05:14.575
It's not about murder,
it's about family.

05:14.618 --> 05:17.882
Vito Corleone
is like King Lear,

05:17.926 --> 05:20.407
except he has sons
instead of daughters.

05:20.450 --> 05:22.365
He is searching

05:22.409 --> 05:24.106
for who is going to be
his legacy.

05:24.149 --> 05:26.413
And yes, in the meantime,
he's gonna do whatever he can

05:26.456 --> 05:29.329
to provide,
to protect his family,

05:29.372 --> 05:32.462
and, yes, as a last resort,
maybe a little bit of murder.

05:32.506 --> 05:34.029
Did you eat my ham?

05:36.292 --> 05:37.641
No.

05:37.685 --> 05:41.515
There was a ham sandwich
in the refrigerator.

05:41.558 --> 05:44.387
I did not eat
the ham sandwich, Mario.

05:44.431 --> 05:47.042
You ate the ham sandwich.
I watched you eat it.

05:47.085 --> 05:49.610
It's not something
I will soon forget.

05:49.653 --> 05:51.481
What the hell was I saying?

05:51.525 --> 05:53.570
The Don wants peace.
Yes.

05:53.614 --> 05:55.442
He's ruthless
when he chooses to be.

05:55.485 --> 05:59.837
Yes. Yes. And that--
that is why he inspires fear,

05:59.881 --> 06:01.230
because of his confidence.

06:01.273 --> 06:02.884
He has immense power.

06:02.927 --> 06:04.668
He doesn't have to flaunt it.

06:04.712 --> 06:06.714
Unlike every single
studio exec I've ever met

06:06.757 --> 06:09.760
who can't wait to tell you
how well-endowed he is

06:09.804 --> 06:11.980
or better yet,
that he has the great idea

06:12.023 --> 06:13.721
that's gonna save your picture.

06:13.764 --> 06:14.765
You're gonna see.

06:14.809 --> 06:16.767
Evans, he's gonna want to cast

06:16.811 --> 06:19.204
Steve McQueen as the Don.

06:19.248 --> 06:20.641
No, I don't see anybody
but Brando in that role.

06:20.684 --> 06:23.818
Ugh, Brando.

06:23.861 --> 06:25.254
Brando is...

06:26.864 --> 06:28.431
Brando is the golden goose.

06:28.475 --> 06:31.869
He's--he's Brando.

06:31.913 --> 06:34.611
You wouldn't have to write any
character to stand up and say,

06:34.655 --> 06:36.308
"Ooh, that's the Godfather."

06:36.352 --> 06:39.268
You would see him
and you would just know it.

06:43.141 --> 06:45.405
I wrote him a letter.

06:45.448 --> 06:46.928
I sent him a signed copy
of the book.

06:46.971 --> 06:48.973
Huh.
You never know.

06:49.017 --> 06:50.540
Fingers crossed, right?

06:52.412 --> 06:53.674
Fingers crossed.

06:56.807 --> 06:58.330
Fingers crossed.

06:58.374 --> 07:01.464
What's wrong, Francis?
W--what's going on?

07:01.508 --> 07:03.292
I mean,
this is all good stuff.

07:03.335 --> 07:04.554
This is great stuff.

07:04.598 --> 07:06.426
This is all great stuff.

07:06.469 --> 07:09.037
But I can't kid myself.

07:09.080 --> 07:12.562
We are trying to write a movie
about an American family

07:12.606 --> 07:14.608
that happens to be
in the crime business.

07:14.651 --> 07:16.610
And, yes,
it's a commentary about

07:16.653 --> 07:19.395
how greed will often lead
to murder

07:19.439 --> 07:21.266
under the guise of business.

07:21.310 --> 07:23.573
I don't think
that's gonna sit very well

07:23.617 --> 07:25.314
with Evans and his bunch

07:25.357 --> 07:28.186
because at the end of the day,
no matter what he pretends,

07:28.230 --> 07:29.927
he is that capitalist.

07:29.971 --> 07:32.147
And we're gonna walk into
this little creative meeting,

07:32.190 --> 07:35.280
I have no idea why.

07:35.324 --> 07:39.502
They want their typical
little gangster flick.

07:43.724 --> 07:45.421
I'm loving you, Mario,

07:45.465 --> 07:47.641
but I have to keep
reminding myself

07:47.684 --> 07:51.079
that this is just a payday,
and I hate that.

07:51.122 --> 07:53.995
Just, uh, keep--keep working.

08:00.741 --> 08:03.352
I think
this is the part

08:03.395 --> 08:05.006
where you're supposed
to ask me if I'm all right.

08:05.049 --> 08:06.355
Listen, I won't judge you

08:06.398 --> 08:08.575
if you need to walk away
from this.

08:08.618 --> 08:10.359
I'll help you find another gig,

08:10.402 --> 08:12.404
make sure you land
on your feet.

08:13.449 --> 08:15.973
You're still gonna try
and make this thing?

08:18.889 --> 08:21.936
When I was a kid,
I was small.

08:23.938 --> 08:26.288
I mean, like really small.

08:26.331 --> 08:30.553
Like a full head shorter
than all my classmates.

08:30.597 --> 08:33.774
And there was this one guy
who just had it out for me.

08:33.817 --> 08:35.906
His name was Marcus Anderson.

08:37.604 --> 08:39.519
I don't even know
why he didn't like me but--

08:39.562 --> 08:42.173
but he didn't.

08:42.217 --> 08:45.525
This one day,
he comes up to me and he says,

08:45.568 --> 08:48.049
"I'm gonna kick your fucking
ass today after school."

08:50.094 --> 08:52.706
And I was--I was scared.

08:55.056 --> 08:58.320
And I could've told a teacher,

08:58.363 --> 09:02.063
I could've went a different
way home, but I didn't.

09:02.106 --> 09:04.021
I waited for him
right out front.

09:06.023 --> 09:07.634
I didn't hide.

09:09.157 --> 09:11.463
Let me guess--you beat
the crap out of him?

09:11.507 --> 09:12.595
No.

09:12.639 --> 09:14.597
He kicked my fucking ass.

09:16.686 --> 09:18.558
He was a big guy.

09:18.601 --> 09:19.776
You should've seen him.

09:21.952 --> 09:23.563
Oh, fuck that guy.

09:25.565 --> 09:28.959
That's a--that's a real
uplifting story, Rud.

09:29.003 --> 09:31.396
Yeah. No, he did.
He kicked my fucking ass.

09:33.442 --> 09:36.271
But I put up a good fight.

09:36.314 --> 09:37.620
And you know what?

09:37.664 --> 09:40.405
After that,
he never fucked with me again.

09:43.452 --> 09:46.368
I can't go back
to that cubicle at Rand.

09:48.109 --> 09:51.242
But I understand
if you need to cut and run.

09:53.114 --> 09:54.985
I'm not running either.

10:00.556 --> 10:03.690
So what's the move now then?

10:03.733 --> 10:06.388
You gonna go punch
Mickey Cohen?

10:06.431 --> 10:08.042
No.

10:08.085 --> 10:10.044
But I am gonna talk to him.

10:33.110 --> 10:35.504
Happy, eh?
That suit's not Czech,

10:35.547 --> 10:37.027
that is Yugoslavian.

10:46.167 --> 10:47.864
I'm so glad you came.I've missed you.

10:47.908 --> 10:49.866
Would you watch him?
Just watch him.

10:49.910 --> 10:51.781
Jesus Christ, guy's an animal.

10:53.914 --> 10:55.611
You're talking about franchise?

10:55.655 --> 10:57.004
I was, like, "What the fuck
is he talking about?"

10:57.047 --> 10:59.528
But he goes, "Like
I wouldn't throw your ball?"

11:04.098 --> 11:05.708
I broke my own rule.
I started talking shop.

11:05.752 --> 11:07.536
Goddamn it!

11:11.540 --> 11:14.586
I kind of like it.
It's like gladiators.

11:14.630 --> 11:17.198
When are you gonna
put me in the movies, Bob?

11:18.678 --> 11:20.549
Christy,
you're already in the movies.

11:20.592 --> 11:22.812
Shh.
I'm just saying.

11:24.074 --> 11:25.728
I love your work, girls.

12:19.086 --> 12:20.957
Where are you right now?

12:23.481 --> 12:25.266
In the best dream
I've ever had.

12:25.309 --> 12:27.572
You're so full of shit.

12:27.616 --> 12:29.792
You're hiding something.

12:29.836 --> 12:32.795
If you don't want to tell me,
you don't have to.

12:32.839 --> 12:34.492
It's work stuff.

12:34.536 --> 12:36.756
Maybe I can help.

12:38.932 --> 12:40.672
I'm putting together budgets,
and nobody will give me

12:40.716 --> 12:43.414
a straight answer
on union requirements.

12:43.458 --> 12:45.373
Everyone's all nervous
about some guy, Mickey Cohen.

12:45.416 --> 12:46.548
Mickey Cohen?

12:46.591 --> 12:48.158
You know him?

12:48.202 --> 12:49.638
Cohen's a criminal.

12:49.681 --> 12:51.814
He's a--he's a--
he's a low life.

12:51.858 --> 12:53.598
A thug.

12:54.817 --> 12:56.776
He, um--

12:56.819 --> 12:58.299
he came to the Chateau
a few years ago.

12:58.342 --> 13:01.041
It was--

13:01.084 --> 13:03.521
It was right after my divorce.

13:03.565 --> 13:06.829
He said he would
do me a favor and--and--

13:06.873 --> 13:08.700
and bring his business
to the Chateau.

13:08.744 --> 13:11.529
All it would take was for me to
use him as my kitchen supplier.

13:11.573 --> 13:13.880
I said "No, no, thank you."
Very nicely.

13:13.923 --> 13:16.534
And then he said,
"You need friends now."

13:16.578 --> 13:18.406
He threatened you?

13:20.887 --> 13:24.020
I ordered two glasses
of a very nice champagne,

13:24.064 --> 13:26.806
I handed him one.

13:26.849 --> 13:28.677
I looked at him

13:28.720 --> 13:31.854
and then I told him, "I faced
the Nazis and survived.

13:31.898 --> 13:33.900
Do you think
I'm afraid of you?"

13:37.817 --> 13:39.166
We clinked glasses, we drank,

13:39.209 --> 13:41.777
and he never came back
to the Chateau.

13:42.909 --> 13:45.520
He prefers the Oyster House.

13:46.434 --> 13:49.437
Baby,
you are a fucking badass.

13:49.480 --> 13:51.743
A badass who still thinks
you're hiding something.

14:02.102 --> 14:03.843
Okay, pack 'em up
and get 'em out of here.

14:03.886 --> 14:05.888
Make sure they're on time.

14:05.932 --> 14:07.847
You got it, Mickey.

14:10.066 --> 14:12.329
Is that him?

14:18.422 --> 14:21.643
You got some balls
coming in here.

14:21.686 --> 14:25.342
I just want to understand
what I did to offend you.

14:25.386 --> 14:27.823
Me? No, no, it's not me.

14:27.867 --> 14:30.565
I can give a fuck
about what you do.

14:30.608 --> 14:33.394
But they...

14:33.437 --> 14:36.266
they don't want you
making this movie.

14:36.310 --> 14:38.703
They say it's disrespectful.

14:38.747 --> 14:40.357
Who's they?

14:40.401 --> 14:43.317
The Italians back east.

14:43.360 --> 14:44.448
You're making a movie about 'em

14:44.492 --> 14:46.233
and you don't know
who they are?

14:46.276 --> 14:47.887
The movie's fictional.

14:47.930 --> 14:51.020
It's not about anybody
in real life.

14:51.064 --> 14:53.414
Except Sinatra, right?

14:53.457 --> 14:55.372
Listen, Al,

14:55.416 --> 14:56.896
I ain't here
to tell you what to do,

14:56.939 --> 14:58.506
but here's the story.

14:58.549 --> 15:00.160
My friends asked me
to deliver a message,

15:00.203 --> 15:01.639
and I delivered that message.

15:01.683 --> 15:04.033
Anything beyond that,
I got no part of.

15:07.123 --> 15:09.256
How do I deal
with your friends?

15:09.299 --> 15:11.127
You want my best advice?

15:12.302 --> 15:14.957
Make a different movie.

15:15.001 --> 15:17.525
And if I don't want to make
a different movie?

15:23.183 --> 15:26.142
Oh, well, then eventually,

15:26.186 --> 15:28.449
you're gonna have to
deal with them directly, Al.

15:28.492 --> 15:31.452
And when that time comes,
and it will,

15:31.495 --> 15:35.195
above all,
be a straight shooter.

15:35.238 --> 15:36.805
They don't fire warning shots.

15:43.768 --> 15:45.683
He just had to handle
something, but he will be here.

15:45.727 --> 15:47.207
Christ!

15:47.250 --> 15:49.122
Are these, uh,
for everyone?What?

15:49.165 --> 15:50.732
Hello, everybody.

15:50.775 --> 15:52.603
Uh, where's Ruddy?

15:52.647 --> 15:54.083
Oh, he's just running
a little behind.

15:54.127 --> 15:55.998
But he said
we can go ahead and start.

15:56.042 --> 15:58.479
All right. All right, yes.

16:01.221 --> 16:04.093
Well, we're all
very excited to be here.

16:04.137 --> 16:06.269
Francis, you know Peter.

16:06.313 --> 16:08.968
And this is Andrea Eastwood,
head of casting.

16:09.011 --> 16:11.971
Now, I know that you and Mario
are deep into the process,

16:12.014 --> 16:13.973
but we just all wanted
to make sure

16:14.016 --> 16:15.975
that we're on
the same page creatively.

16:16.018 --> 16:18.412
Why don't you tell us
what you're thinking?

16:19.717 --> 16:21.241
Sure.

16:22.198 --> 16:24.766
Sure.

16:24.809 --> 16:26.898
Okay, um--

16:26.942 --> 16:28.596
It's actually
coming along really well.

16:30.076 --> 16:32.078
That's one hell
of a paperweight you got there.

16:32.121 --> 16:34.167
Okay, um--

16:35.516 --> 16:38.693
So tonally, thematically,

16:38.736 --> 16:40.695
this whole picture,

16:40.738 --> 16:43.437
it's about light and darkness.

16:43.480 --> 16:47.049
You have the bright celebration
of Connie's wedding

16:47.093 --> 16:49.965
against the dark underbelly
of Don Corleone's business.

16:50.009 --> 16:51.401
I love that. Mm.

16:51.445 --> 16:53.490
Then we introduce Michael.

16:53.534 --> 16:55.971
And Michael,
he's straddling the two worlds.

16:56.015 --> 16:58.930
When we first meet him,
he's very much in the light.

16:58.974 --> 17:01.107
And then,
when he comes to the wedding,

17:01.150 --> 17:04.327
I think that he should be
in full uniform, okay?

17:04.371 --> 17:06.721
He's got the colorful medals,
it's, like, uh, he's glowing.

17:06.764 --> 17:08.070
It's just after World War II,

17:08.114 --> 17:09.550
and Michael
represents hope again

17:09.593 --> 17:10.986
after a time
of great depression.

17:11.030 --> 17:12.118
Excellent, Peter.
Thank you.

17:12.161 --> 17:13.554
Yeah, I can think of
a dozen actors

17:13.597 --> 17:15.077
that would love to sink
their teeth into that.

17:15.121 --> 17:16.731
Oh, hell, yeah.

17:16.774 --> 17:17.993
I think that
when we eventually shoot this

17:18.037 --> 17:19.560
that, uh,
the whole look of the film

17:19.603 --> 17:21.605
should reflect this opposition
of the light and the dark.

17:21.649 --> 17:23.433
Make it feel real.

17:23.477 --> 17:25.218
None of these caricatures
of what a gangster is.

17:25.261 --> 17:26.697
Yeah, they're family men,

17:26.741 --> 17:28.090
they're--they're--
they're businessmen, you know,

17:28.134 --> 17:29.483
they could be your neighbor.

17:29.526 --> 17:31.224
I'm pretty sure
one of them is.

17:33.965 --> 17:35.619
Hey, Barry.

17:35.663 --> 17:37.360
I'm sorry, I thought you were
on the way to the airport.

17:37.404 --> 17:38.622
Do you need something?

17:38.666 --> 17:40.015
Oh, no, thanks, Bob.

17:40.059 --> 17:41.799
Appreciate you asking though.

17:41.843 --> 17:44.106
Everyone,
this is Barry Lapidus,

17:44.150 --> 17:46.065
Gulf and Western's
shining star,

17:46.108 --> 17:48.328
and Jack Ballard,
who runs physical production.

17:48.371 --> 17:49.981
Hey, Jack.

17:50.025 --> 17:52.462
Look, uh,
I'm a little tied up right now.

17:52.506 --> 17:54.290
Can I come and see you after?

17:54.334 --> 17:55.726
Oh, no.
That won't be necessary.

17:55.770 --> 17:58.077
This meeting is the reason
